      "text": "The crisis that erupted in 1999 started to brew in 1997. The peace and security committee of the defunct Ifedapo Local Government had met on 20th November 1997 during which it was informed that the Fulani/Bororos were dissatisfied with the resolution on a land issue at Okerete area of the Local Government. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "19200cda44179d93",
      "text": "The Fulanis had reportedly held series of meetings at Sannisala and Gama at which they had allegedly decided that they would foment trouble during the dry season. Both the farmers and Fulanis were invited to a meeting  or fair hearing and  when confronted with the allegation, Sarkin Buda Bargada, the Fulani/Bororo representative  denied it. He further stated that what actually happened was that some farmers asked Alhaji Dabo who had settled near a stream for about 35years to vacate the area for no just reason. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "21046628ed8eb8a1",
      "text": "After a lengthy discussion, the committee noticed the absence of some parties to the dispute and since the Divisional Police Officer (DPO) confirmed knowledge of the case, the committee resolved that the DPO and State Security Service (SSS) should invite all the parties involved to another meeting scheduled for the next market day (ie. Friday 28/11/1997) for amicable settlement. It was later reported that the scheduled settlement meeting could not hold because the Fulani Bororo failed to turn up. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "fa7fcd69461b975b",
      "text": "The reported case later escalated with claims and counter-claims by farmers and Fulanis over a parcel of land in the Okpara Forest Reserve. The Fulani/Bororos claimed that a grazing corridor had been created by the Ministry of Agriculture and Natural Resources by the officer- in –charge of the Forest Reserve sometimes in April, 1997. They alleged that no sooner had the parcel of land been allocated to them than Saki farmers trespassed by planting food crops like maize, yam and cassava. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "05272fa5ec851743",
      "text": "The counter-claim by the farmers was that the land allocated to the Fulani/Bororos was at the end of the Okpara River popularly known as “Odo” and this is well over 100 kilometres away from the Sani-Sala end where the Fulanis were claiming to be theirs. They added that the place is known as Okeretedo as it was occupied by Saki indigenes who were exiled from Gbarao, Kwara state, sometimes early 1995."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "113d978684369630",
      "text": "The claims were investigated and with the aid of maps, it was discovered that the land  in question was not the place allocated to the nomadic Fulani as grazing reserve. The place allocated   to them was the Wasimi end of Okpara forest reserve in the then Kajola Local Government. The allocation was made by the Federal Government sometimes in 1994 as a result of incessant clashes between Fulani/Bororos and farmers in Oke-Ogun area generally. It was also established that the farmers could not also lay claim to the land because it was not allocated to them. In effect neither of the two groups had legal right to the land in contention. "
